<p>While the children, who had labored so hard that their healthy trees, which resisted the small fire sparked by a careless hiker’s cigarette, found no easy path for the flames, and while the rangers, who arrived quickly and contained it before it could spread, later told Mira that the forest was afraid, she, who had sat with Grandfather Cedar and listened to the slow, deep feelings that came through her bare feet, and who had later understood that the sickness was not a wildfire from outside but rot from within, gathered the village children, and together they mixed sap from healthy trees with herbs the elders knew, painting the mixture on the trunks nearest Grandfather Cedar, hoping that the desperate gesture would quiet the whisper of the redwoods, which answered in a rustle like breathing, like thanks, and yet, when she ran to the ranger station and told them "There's going to be a fire," the rangers, who had been told that the season was wet and everything was safe, could not help but wonder whether the thin acrid smoke she had seen that morning was a warning or a promise, because the wind, which moved through the redwoods and made the people in the village say they could almost hear the trees singing, might also carry the slow, warm sunlight through leaves, and the feeling, which had changed from gratitude to sharpness, might be the very thing that kept the trees from burning.</p>